05266nam a22007095i 9780226635491DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226635491  a(DE-B1597)545018  a(OCoLC)1143833503  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBF1028 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a130.941/090341 aRaia, Courtenay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New Prometheans :bFaith, Science, and the Supernatural Mind in the Victorian Fin de Siècle /cCourtenay Raia. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b4 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. The Culture of Proof and the Crisis of Faith -- tChapter Two. William Crookes in Wonderland: Scientific Spiritualism and the Physics of the Impossible -- tChapter Three. Romancing the Crone: Frederic Myers, Spiritualism, and the “Enchanted Portal to the World” -- tChapter Four. “The Incandescent Solid beneath Our Line of Sight”: Frederic Myers, the Self, and the Psychiatric Subconscious -- tChapter Five. Knowledge in Motion: Oliver Lodge, the Imperceptible Ether, and the Physics of (Extra-) Sensory Perception -- tChapter Six. Uncanny Cavemen: Andrew Lang, Psycho-Folklore, and the Romance of Ancient Man -- tChapter Seven. Psychical Modernism: Science, Subjectivity, and the Unsalvageable Self -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Society for Psychical Research was established in 1882 to further the scientific study of consciousness, but it arose in the surf of a larger cultural need. Victorians were on the hunt for self-understanding. Mesmerists, spiritualists, and other romantic seekers roamed sunken landscapes of entrancement, and when psychology was finally ready to confront these altered states, psychical research was adopted as an experimental vanguard. Far from a rejected science, it was a necessary heterodoxy, probing mysteries as diverse as telepathy, hypnosis, and even séance phenomena. Its investigators sought facts far afield of physical laws: evidence of a transcendent, irreducible mind. The New Prometheans traces the evolution of psychical research through the intertwining biographies of four men: chemist Sir William Crookes, depth psychologist Frederic Myers, ether physicist Sir Oliver Lodge, and anthropologist Andrew Lang. All past presidents of the society, these men brought psychical research beyond academic circles and into the public square, making it part of a shared, far-reaching examination of science and society. By layering their papers, textbooks, and lectures with more intimate texts like diaries, letters, and literary compositions, Courtenay Raia returns us to a critical juncture in the history of secularization, the last great gesture of reconciliation between science and sacred truths.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCrookes, William,-1832-1919. 0aParapsychologyzEnglandxHistory. 0aSupernaturalxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAndrew Lang.  aFrederic Myers.  aOliver Lodge.  aVictorian supernatural.  aWilliam Crookes.  aepistemology.  anineteenth-century spiritualism.  aparapsychology.  apsychical research.  ascience vs. religion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE His